</figure>
<p>Our diagnostic fee gets waived when you proceed with the repair, and we provide a transparent quote showing exactly what parts are needed. Most flow sense error repairs involve either thorough vent system cleaning, sensor replacement, or ductwork modifications - all of which we handle during the same visit with our 1-year warranty on parts and labor.</p>
<h2>Why Professional Repair Beats DIY for Flow Sense Errors</h2>
<p>Flow sense errors require specialized diagnostic equipment that homeowners don't typically own - trying to guess whether it's the sensor, ductwork, or external blockage often leads to buying unnecessary parts. Our technicians carry airflow meters, duct inspection cameras, and the complete range of OEM sensors for all LG models including DLGX, DLEX, and DLE series. The safety factor becomes critical when dealing with external vent cleaning - we've seen DIY attempts damage roof vents or create fire hazards from improper ductwork connections. Professional repair also means understanding the interaction between the flow sense system and other components - a failing sensor might mask <a href="/symptoms/lg-dryer-not-heating/">LG dryer not heating</a> issues that need simultaneous attention. Our 85% first-visit fix rate comes from carrying the right parts and having the diagnostic experience to identify root causes immediately. DIY repairs often address symptoms rather than causes, leading to recurring flow sense errors within weeks.</p>
<h2>Flow Sense Error Repair Cost vs Replacement Analysis</h2>
<p>Most LG dryer flow sense error repairs range from $280–380 including parts and labor, depending on whether the issue requires sensor replacement, ductwork modification, or comprehensive vent cleaning. Compare this to purchasing a new LG dryer, which runs $800-1500 for comparable models, plus installation and disposal fees. The repair cost breaks down into diagnostic service, OEM parts (flow sensors typically cost $65-120), and labor for proper installation and testing. In our experience serving Santa Monica and Newport Beach, about 50% of flow sense error calls turn out to be service-only visits costing $65-120 for thorough cleaning and system resets. When sensor replacement is needed, we show clients the exact part cost on supplier websites for complete transparency. Our flexible pricing policy means if we have the required sensor in warehouse stock purchased at lower prices, those savings get passed directly to you. Replacing a 3-7 year old LG dryer for a flow sense error rarely makes financial sense, especially considering our repairs come with full warranty coverage and the reliability of OEM parts.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>What causes LG dryer flow sense error codes?</h3>
<p>Flow sense errors occur when restricted airflow triggers the dryer's safety system. Common causes include blocked external vents, lint buildup in internal ductwork, or a failing flow sense sensor.</p>
<h3>Can I fix LG dryer flow sense error myself?</h3>
<p>While basic lint cleaning helps, flow sense errors usually require specialized diagnostic equipment to identify whether the sensor, ductwork, or external blockage is the root cause. Professional diagnosis prevents unnecessary part purchases.</p>
<h3>How long does flow sense error repair take?</h3>
<p>Most flow sense error repairs take 45-90 minutes depending on whether sensor replacement or ductwork modification is needed. Our technicians carry common parts for same-day completion.</p>
<h3>Will flow sense error damage my LG dryer?</h3>
<p>Continued operation with flow sense errors can overheat the heating element and trigger thermal fuse failures. Addressing the error promptly prevents more expensive secondary damage.</p>
<h3>How much does LG dryer flow sense error repair cost?</h3>
<p>Repair costs typically range $280–380 including parts and labor, though simple cleaning and resets may cost only $65-120. Call (323) 990-7550 for an accurate quote based on your specific model and symptoms.</p>
<h3>What do the d80, d90, and d95 codes mean on my LG dryer?</h3>
<p>They're flow sense codes that measure how restricted your exhaust airflow is — d80 means roughly 80% blockage, with d90 and d95 closer to fully blocked. They almost always point to a clogged vent or lint-packed ductwork rather than a broken dryer. Our techs measure actual vent airflow and test the flow sense sensor before replacing anything. We're Bureau of Household Goods licensed (#49573).</p>
<h3>How can I prevent LG dryer flow sense errors?</h3>
<p>Keep the airflow path clear: clean the lint screen every load, have the full vent run professionally cleaned once a year, and replace long flexible ducting with rigid metal where you can. Most flow sense errors we see trace back to a vent that hasn't been cleaned in years. Our LG Dryer Repair techs clear the vent and verify airflow on every flow sense call so the code doesn't come back.</p>

